      "note_no": "21",
      "note": "The term wajh (lit., \"face\") occurring here is often used, in the abstract sense, to denote a person's entire being or entire attention - as, for instance, in the phrase aslamtu wajhi li'llahi, \"I have surrendered my whole being unto God\" (3:20). The word masjid, which usually signifies the time or place of prostration in prayer (sujud), evidently stands in this context - as well as in verse 31 below - for any act of worship."
